    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a41ab224_042b6a6d",
        "filename": "build/find_mac_sdk.py",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 29,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-06T22:07:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We shouldn’t be building up SDK paths manually.\n\n“xcrun --show-sdk-path” will assemble a path to the default SDK.\n\n“xcrun --show-sdk-path --sdk macosx10.12” will assemble a path to the 10.12 SDK.\n\nSince you won’t be doing anything with the output other than just reprinting it, you can move from subprocess.check_output to subprocess.check_call.",
      "revId": "90b3472c19ae362f7f5c036ae164616985f5073b",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ae5a2dbb_5bbdb8e4",
        "filename": "build/find_mac_sdk.py",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 33,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-06T22:07:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "You don’t have to, but I prefer to invoke main with sys.argv[1:], and to then just use those args directly in main() without having to worry about skipping [0].",
      "revId": "90b3472c19ae362f7f5c036ae164616985f5073b",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "12500aaf_a98a48af",
        "filename": "util/BUILD.gn",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 20,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-06T22:07:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don’t want to have a hard-coded default for this. See comments in the .py file.\n\nWhy? For the past few years, Apple’s only been shipping a single SDK version with each copy of Xcode. The Xcode 8 series contains the macOS 10.12 SDK, and I guess that’s what you’re using. But Xcode 9 is current, and it contains the macOS 10.13 SDK. It’s not necessarily entirely unreasonable for you (or someone else) to be using Xcode 8 still, but neither is it unreasonable for someone else to be using 9 as I am. And the only way to support both in the same tree without requiring everyone to write their SDK version down in args.gn is to respect whatever happens to be present as the default.",
      "revId": "90b3472c19ae362f7f5c036ae164616985f5073b",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1cc50560_69e3e44d",
        "filename": "util/BUILD.gn",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 25,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-06T22:15:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "sysroot (in the style of this .gni) may not be the most unreasonable thing to have available in the standalone Crashpad build, considering the various cross targets we want to support. You’re already working with sysroot for Fuchsia in mini_chromium’s build/BUILD.gn. Should we go ahead and do a //build/config/sysroot.gni here too, and move your find_mac_sdk.py to it? It’d eliminate this use of crashpad_in_chromium.",
      "revId": "90b3472c19ae362f7f5c036ae164616985f5073b",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
